04406nam a22004575i 9780226470771DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20092009ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226470771  a(DE-B1597)523841  a(OCoLC)593222255  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aPOL0000002bisacsh1 aLee, Frances E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond Ideology :bPolitics, Principles, and Partisanship in the U. S. Senate /cFrances E. Lee. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b29 line drawings, 24 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Ties That Bind: Untangling the Roots of Congressional Partisanship -- tChapter 2. Before “Ideology”: A Conceptual History -- tChapter 3. Sources of Party Conflict: Ideological Disagreement and Teamsmanship -- tChapter 4. Dividers, Not Uniters: Presidential Leadership and Legislative Partisanship -- tChapter 5. The Partisan Politics of Good Government -- tChapter 6. Procedural Partisanship: Intra-Party Dealmaking and Partisan Bloc Voting -- tChapter 7. Agreeing to Disagree, or Disagreeing to Agree: Agenda Content and Rising Partisanship -- tChapter 8. Beyond Ideology: Returning to Politics -- tAppendix a. Coding the Presidential Agenda Status of Roll-Call Votes -- tAppendix b. Does Party Polarization on an Issue Topic Increase the Likelihood that Presidents Will Include the Issue on Their Agenda? -- tAppendix c. Estimates of Multinomial Logit Model of Partisan Voting Patterns on Senate Roll-Call Votes, 1981–2004 -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe congressional agenda, Frances Lee contends, includes many issues about which liberals and conservatives generally agree. Even over these matters, though, Democratic and Republican senators tend to fight with each other. What explains this discord? Beyond Ideology argues that many partisan battles are rooted in competition for power rather than disagreement over the rightful role of government. The first book to systematically distinguish Senate disputes centering on ideological questions from the large proportion of them that do not, this volume foregrounds the role of power struggle in partisan conflict. Presidential leadership, for example, inherently polarizes legislators who can influence public opinion of the president and his party by how they handle his agenda. Senators also exploit good government measures and floor debate to embarrass opponents and burnish their own party’s image—even when the issues involved are broadly supported or low-stakes. Moreover, Lee contends, the congressional agenda itself amplifies conflict by increasingly focusing on issues that reliably differentiate the parties. With the new president pledging to stem the tide of partisan polarization, Beyond Ideology provides a timely taxonomy of exactly what stands in his way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPolitical partiesxUnited States. 0aPolitical partieszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apartisanship, power, competition, congress, politics, political science, senate, conflict, disagreement, across the aisle, social issues, government, liberals, conservatives, democrats, republicans, polarization, public opinion, floor debate, party, legislators, presidency, difference, nonfiction, ideology, bloc voting, dealmaking, roll-call votes.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226470771423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226470771/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles